1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,160
Hello and welcome to In Simple Terms with Satish.

2
00:00:03,160 --> 00:00:05,400
Today we are talking about Vibe Coding.

3
00:00:05,400 --> 00:00:10,920
The idea that you can build software by talking to an AI coding tool instead of typing every

4
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:12,200
line yourself.

5
00:00:12,200 --> 00:00:14,240
Let us start with the technology first.

6
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:16,720
Vibe Coding is a new developer loop.

7
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:19,260
You describe what you want in normal language.

8
00:00:19,260 --> 00:00:22,340
The coding assistant reads some project context.

9
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:24,480
It suggests or edits code.

10
00:00:24,480 --> 00:00:26,660
It may run tests or commands.

11
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:29,680
Then you inspect the result and ask for changes.

12
00:00:29,680 --> 00:00:34,760
So the code editor starts feeling less like a blank page and more like a conversation.

13
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:38,000
Let us understand this with a simple everyday example.

14
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:39,960
Imagine you are setting up a room for studying.

15
00:00:39,960 --> 00:00:45,720
In the old way, you move every chair, plug in every cable, choose every lamp and organize

16
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:47,320
every book yourself.

17
00:00:47,320 --> 00:00:49,840
Now imagine you have a very fast assistant.

18
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:52,440
You say, make this room better for studying.

19
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:57,800
The assistant moves the desk, adds a lamp, clears the table and organizes the books.

20
00:00:57,800 --> 00:01:00,960
That sounds powerful, but you still have to check the result.

21
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:03,160
Maybe the assistant blocked the power outlet.

22
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:04,920
Maybe the lamp creates glare.

23
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:08,200
Maybe an important notebook was thrown into the wrong shelf.

24
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:12,000
The assistant saved effort, but you still own the judgment.

25
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:13,640
Vibe Coding works the same way.

26
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:18,480
The AI can create the first draft of code quickly, but the engineer still has to check

27
00:01:18,480 --> 00:01:22,780
whether the code is correct, secure, understandable and maintainable.

28
00:01:22,780 --> 00:01:25,560
Now return to the actual technical concept.

29
00:01:25,560 --> 00:01:28,860
Human AI coding tools are moving beyond autocomplete.

30
00:01:28,860 --> 00:01:34,360
They can read files, understand error logs, edit multiple parts of a project, run tests

31
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:36,640
and return a diff for review.

32
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:41,880
Some tools can even work in the background, on a branch or in a sandbox while the developer

33
00:01:41,880 --> 00:01:43,660
reviews the result later.

34
00:01:43,660 --> 00:01:46,200
Under the hood, the loop has several layers.

35
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:47,560
First, Intent.

36
00:01:47,560 --> 00:01:49,360
The human explains the goal.

37
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:50,680
Second, Context.

38
00:01:50,680 --> 00:01:56,200
The tool needs relevant files, tests, framework rules, logs and constraints.

39
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:57,640
Third, Generation.

40
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:00,520
The model predicts a possible code change.

41
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:02,020
Fourth, Execution.

42
00:02:02,020 --> 00:02:05,520
The tool may run tests, type checks or build commands.

43
00:02:05,520 --> 00:02:06,760
Fifth, Review.

44
00:02:06,760 --> 00:02:10,000
The human reads the diff and decides what survives.

45
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:11,960
That last step is the catch.

46
00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:16,160
Code generation is becoming cheaper, but verification is not free.

47
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:21,240
AI generated code can look confident and still call the wrong function, miss an edge

48
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:25,280
case, weaken security or make the system harder to maintain.

49
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:28,640
This is why wipe coding does not mean engineers disappear.

50
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:31,600
It means the engineer's job moves up a level.

51
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:34,180
Instead of only asking, can I write this function?

52
00:02:34,180 --> 00:02:37,660
The better questions are, did the tool understand the requirement?

53
00:02:37,660 --> 00:02:39,280
Did it touch the right files?

54
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:41,400
Did the tests prove the behavior?

55
00:02:41,400 --> 00:02:43,840
Can another developer maintain this later?

56
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:45,400
For students, this is important.

57
00:02:45,640 --> 00:02:49,440
AI can help you build faster, but do not skip the basics.

58
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:50,880
Learn how the code works.

59
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:52,640
Read the error messages.

60
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:53,780
Understand the data flow.

61
00:02:53,780 --> 00:02:55,280
Write small tests.

62
00:02:55,280 --> 00:02:56,280
Review the diff.

63
00:02:56,280 --> 00:02:59,280
For professional engineers, the lesson is even sharper.

64
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:04,160
Treat AI output like a very fast junior developer's pull request.

65
00:03:04,160 --> 00:03:07,640
Useful, sometimes impressive, but still needing review.

66
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:09,840
The real skill is not just prompting.

67
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:14,480
It is giving clear constraints, supplying the right context, checking the result and

68
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:18,520
knowing when to stop asking the AI and read the code yourself.

69
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:22,440
That is why the best prompts are not only creative, they are specific.

70
00:03:22,440 --> 00:03:26,800
They say what should change, what should not change and how the result will be checked.

71
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:28,720
The clear takeaway is this.

72
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:34,560
Wipe coding makes programming feel more conversational, but software still has to survive reality.

73
00:03:34,560 --> 00:03:40,580
It must run, pass tests, handle edge cases, protect users and make sense to the next person

74
00:03:40,580 --> 00:03:41,580
who reads it.

75
00:03:41,580 --> 00:03:45,580
In simple terms, AI can help write the first draft of code.

76
00:03:45,580 --> 00:03:49,420
Engineering is what proves the draft deserves to live in the codebase.

77
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:53,980
If this helped you understand the topic in simple terms, follow or subscribe to In Simple

78
00:03:53,980 --> 00:03:55,180
Terms with Satish.

79
00:03:55,180 --> 00:03:56,900
I will see you in the next episode.
